helpdesk-note.body-html: Moving back to Sys Admin team. Dr. Kaltchev insists on the creation of these accounts.

helpdesk-note.body:
Dr. Kaltchev,
Box.com accounts are associated with users - not mailboxes. The method for using Box would be to create folders in Box, perhaps named "Math" and "Phys_Chem" and share those folders with the users you want associated with the files in those folders. You can administrate multiple users to be the Owners or Editors of these folders, and they will have rights to make changes. You can share the folder by user, by link, or by password.
Unfortunately, Box.com has no integration with our Microsoft Active Directory system, so there is no way to link mailbox accounts to AD groups and assign access to Box automatically. I've added two links at the end of the email, one internal, and one to Box.com's knowledgebase that may help. Please let us know if you need additional assistance.
With the above in mind, do you still want those additional mailboxes? They cannot be set up as generic users, and as such cannot be assigned a Box.com account.
http://www.msoe.edu/docs/DOC-3261 http://boxuniversity.litmos.com/online-courses Thanks

helpdesk-ticket.subject: Unable to log onto MSOE wifi in L307
helpdesk-ticket.description: I am in L307 and am unable to log onto the MSOE WiFi. I am forced to use the guest system. There also are a tremendous number of rogue WiFi systems in the area.
helpdesk-ticket.description-html: I am in L307 and am unable to log onto the MSOE WiFi.  I am forced to use the guest system.  There also are a tremendous number of rogue WiFi systems in the area.

helpdesk-note.body:
Dr. Walter Schilling,
I'm seeing a smaller number of users on all the wireless APs in that area of the library, and the authenticated users are getting decent speeds. Guest speeds are locked at the assigned rate-limit. The APs in this area are set to lower broadcast ranges as not to overlap each other or contest each other for channels, but their lower power settings would not effect authentication. However, if they are competing with outside signals, we cannot control what channels those signals are broadcasting on. Our soft policy is to discourage people from using their own wireless routers on campus as it causes issues in the 2.4ghz range, but we can't stop people from using them, and we have no way to limit external signals - especially near windows.
If your device uses a 5ghz radio, you should have better luck getting and maintaining a signal. We have a plan to refresh the wireless APs across campus in stages. Since the library tends to be a problematic wireless area, we can prioritize this building when the next phase takes place.
You may also wish to disable/forget one of the MSOE wireless SSIDs so that they do not failover between each other. We recommend only having the MSOE-wireless active, but obviously in this case, if you cannot authenticate, guest is your only viable choice.

helpdesk-ticket.description-html:
I have tried various times and multiple ways to migrate over my msoe email to the alumni account and have been unsuccessful. I was also locked out of my MSOE email account over a month ago. I don't know if I can still migrate or not. But if so, How could I go about doing it?

I attached the error I get when I try to do  this.

helpdesk-note.body:
Hi Alexandra,
Unfortunately since you are no longer enrolled at MSOE your msoe.edu email has been disabled (it would've been at the start of the quarter, which may have been what you experienced), so you no longer have access to it. We cannot re-enable the account without you being enrolled so there is no way to forward emails from it to your alumni email.
I'm very sorry, but if there is anything else I can help you with please let me know. I'm very sorry, but if there is anything else I can help you with please let me know.

helpdesk-ticket.subject: Whistling in headphone jack
helpdesk-ticket.description: On my school laptop (hp zbook 15) anytime I plug in a headset into the headphone jack I hear a whistling sound. It only happens when music/sound is playing or was just playing then it turns off. I have tried multiple headphones/headsets so it is the computer doing it.
helpdesk-ticket.description-html: On my school laptop (hp zbook 15) anytime I plug in a headset into the headphone jack I hear a whistling sound. It only happens when music/sound is playing or was just playing then it turns off. I have tried multiple headphones/headsets so it is the computer doing it.

helpdesk-note.body:
Hi Kyle Brown, Issue: http://helpdesk.msoe.edu/helpdesk/tickets/1905
The 'whistling' that you are hearing is actually electrical interference. There is no known fix for this. It has to do with the internal hardware of the laptop.

helpdesk-ticket.subject: Computer Issues
helpdesk-ticket.description: Alana came into the desk having strange issues regarding Multisim, as well as some other programs. We tried reinstalling the programs directly from neo. It seemed to go through the entire installation successfully. However, the programs would not show up in the programs list, and did not seem to actually be installed anywhere on the drive. After talking to Alana, I think the problem may be related to incorrectly uninstalled programs (deleting the folders instead of actually uninstalling -- registry issues). So we are going to perform a fresh image once she is done backing up her files. This ticket does not require follow up, just used for documentation.

helpdesk-note.body:
Hi Sean,
I've been assigning and merging your tickets so that there's only one. You may be getting notices that the tickets are closed when they become merged into a single ticket. We've also closed tickets after verifying network traffic.
As a summary: We've verified the port in the closet to your room 1401-01-A is live in the switch. The port on the switch is showing traffic lights that indicate it is working The physical network team has checked the port in the room directly with a laptop and was able to browse the network from that port The physical network team verified with the building manager's team that there was network to that port When we checked the closet yesterday, there were no lights on the port, but this only indicates there was no device on the other end
From our perspective, the port we believe is 1401-01-A is live and passing network traffic. Can you verify that the device you are using works in another location? Are you using a router or switch, or is this port feeding directly to a computer or device? Will you be available today during business hours to illustrate the exact issue with a technician? While unlikely, it's possible that the port is mislabeled, and shows up in more than one place in your room.
We are also eager to resolve your issue, but we have taken as many steps to verify connectivity that we can. We'll need your help to troubleshoot any further.
Thanks
---

helpdesk-note.body:
Hi Vivian Mickelson,
A box.com folder can be shared with anyone you'd like. It can be shared to individual users, or it can be shared with anyone that has the link, it can be passworded, or made public. However, box.com is not related to MSOE MS Active Directory - meaning there are only folders and accounts for individual users. There are not folders for departments, or groups like in email. The two systems are separate companies (Microsoft and Box) and at this time, there is not a method to combine the folder or group hierarchy.
Below are two links for setting up and using Box. One is a doc created by Mike Timm here at MSOE that is customized to the MSOE environment. The other link comes directly from Box and explains detailed use of their product.
http://www.msoe.edu/docs/DOC-3261 http://boxuniversity.litmos.com/online-courses
I apologize that someone may have suggested to Dr. Barnicki that Box and Microsoft Active Directory were linked, but unfortunately at this time, the companies do not share a method to incorporate group access.
Thanks! Issue: http://helpdesk.msoe.edu/helpdesk/tickets/1934 Good Morning, Dr. Barnicki has learned that it may be possible to have a Box.com account associated with our medeptrequests@msoe.edu email.
If you, kindly let me know how we need to proceed,
Thank you!
helpdesk-note.body-html:
Hi Vivian Mickelson,

A box.com folder can be shared with anyone you'd like. It can be shared to individual users, or it can be shared with anyone that has the link, it can be passworded, or made public. However, box.com is not related to MSOE  MS Active Directory - meaning there are only folders and accounts for individual users. There are not folders for departments, or groups like in email. The two systems are separate companies (Microsoft and Box) and at this time, there is not a method to combine the folder or group hierarchy.

Below are two links for setting up and using Box. One is a doc created by Mike Timm here at MSOE that is customized to the MSOE environment. The other link comes directly from Box and explains detailed use of their product. 

http://www.msoe.edu/docs/DOC-3261
http://boxuniversity.litmos.com/online-courses

I apologize that someone may have suggested to Dr. Barnicki that Box and Microsoft Active Directory were linked, but unfortunately at this time, the companies do not share a method to incorporate group access.

Thanks!

helpdesk-ticket.subject: Data Studio not working
helpdesk-ticket.description: Nicholas was trying to get Data Studio to work on his laptop. It would open but upon clicking anything in the program it would crash. He had uninstalled and reinstalled several times and was following instructions from his professor. One of the steps he skipped was one asking to open a .exe file and run as administrator since it would prompt to uninstall. I ran Data Studio as an admin and it worked fine. Was able to do stuff in the program without freezing. Professor probably meant to run a Data Studio .exe that the shortcut created appears to direct you to.

Hi Sue (and Loreen),
 
I tried to figure out on my own the situation and then with Vivian’s assistance as to why Loreen is not seeing the Men’s Choir Lesson at 7 pm nor the Women’s Choir Rehearsal at 8 pm. I did notice these events  do say “incomplete” and are in red font whereas other items that one can see have a status of “Scheduled” so that may be why.  When I looked up Loreen’s status it appears she can VIEW ALL EVENTS. Unless there is something to not seeing student org events but that would be odd.
 
Since the view is not what is wanted but there are actual events in the time slots backing up to Loreen’s event, how would you like to proceed?
Since these lessons/rehearsal look like they are scheduled out for 34 weeks is there a way to find out if they are indeed rehearsing?
Anne

helpdesk-ticket.description: I am a part-time student and have a laptop that has been giving me issues for a couple years. It overheats and shuts down unless I have an external fan blowing on it. This last Monday 10/12/15, the computer blue screened and shut down. When I tried to start it up, it didn't recognize the boot partition and would not start up. I used a bootable Linux to get my school work off of the non-bootable partition. After this, Windows now boots but it takes minutes to do anything in Matlab or Microsoft Word and is painful to use. The battery is also shot. The bottom line is that I need a different laptop because this one is not cutting it and I think is the last remaining Elite Book 8540w on campus :). I will be coming to IT today, 10/14/15, to see if I can get a different laptop.

helpdesk-note.body:
Guys,
It's still not working. We've power cycled everything. When we turn the printer back on, it prints a test page. The problem is that when someone wants to print something, and they scan their ID card, the printer does not nothing -- it just continues to indicate that it is "ready." We've unplugged and plugged back in the little proximity ID scanner. When you scan an ID card, the red light changes to a green light -- but then nothing else occurs. I just sent a Word document to Follow You printing. I tried to print it on the library small printer -- nothing. I then printed the document successfully on the large printer. We understand that if you try to print something in color, but don't have money on your card, you won't be able to print on the color printer. However, we were told that we could still print black and white documents to the small printer -- and we successfully have done this in the past. Now, we can't get the small printer to do anything, except print a test page.
Would you please take another look at this?
Thanks,
Gary
Library
________________________________

I then printed the document successfully on the large printer.  We understand that if you try to print something in color, but don't have money on your card, you won't be able to print on the color printer.  However, we were told that we could still print black and white documents to the small printer -- and we successfully have done this in the past.  Now, we can't get the small printer to do anything, except print a test page.

Would you please take another look at this?

Thanks,

Gary
Library

helpdesk-note.body:
Hi Carly,
You have full access to the programs available on the msoe network. These programs may only be installed on the laptop the school has provided to you. You can install Autodesk Inventor by going from the Start Menu to Control Panel>Programs and Features>Install a Program off the network. A list of the programs available for you to install will compile.
To be able to use Inventor off campus on your MSOE laptop you will have to download the VPN client GlobalProtect. To install it go to https://sslvpn.msoe.edu/ and login with your MSOE credentials, wait a bit and the "Click to go back to login page" page will change and list what downloads you can do. Select the 64-bit for windows and go through the prompts. Once installed, open GlobalProtect and enter in your username and password. Click send and you should connect. You'll have to do this anytime you are not on the MSOE network and need to use a program.
Does this make sense? Is there anything else I can help you with?

helpdesk-note.body:
Hi Lisa Rebenitsch,
You should try clearing the credential manager. When you click "remember me" when logging in to Outlook, it stores those entered credentials into the windows credential manager. If you change or reset your MSOE credentials, the credential manager is not touched. We can delete the saved credentials from the manager if this is the case. This should force Outlook to ask you for your most recent credentials. Hopefully this will solve your problem.
1. Open the start menu and search "Credential Manager". Click on it. 2. When the window opens, look near the bottom of the window for "Generic Credentials". There should be an entry with a title of something along the lines of "ms.outlook.youremailaddress". Click on that, and choose "Remove from Vault". A warning message will appear. Click yes. 3. Close the credential manager, and close Outlook if it is not already closed. Reopen Outlook and it will ask you for latest credentials. Issue: http://helpdesk.msoe.edu/helpdesk/tickets/2009

I only discovered this after I used gmail to bypass the problem.
I am using gmail as a client, but sending and receiving has worked up till about a week ago.

helpdesk-note.body-html:
Hi Lisa Rebenitsch,

You should try clearing the credential manager. When you click "remember me" when logging in to Outlook, it stores those entered credentials into the windows credential manager. If you change or reset your MSOE credentials, the credential manager is not touched. We can delete the saved credentials from the manager if this is the case. This should force Outlook to ask you for your most recent credentials. Hopefully this will solve your problem.

1. Open the start menu and search "Credential Manager". Click on it.

helpdesk-note.body:
Go to ciscovoicemail.msoe.edu
Log in using your standard email credentials Click “Messaging Assistant” Mouse over the “Password” dropdown menu and choose change pin Using numbers ONLY type the password you want to use for your voice mail. It must be a minimum of 6 characters. Click save and your new voicemail password will be set instantly.
You can only change your password this way 1 time every 24 hours. - See more at: http://www.msoe.edu/docs/DOC-1950#sthash.GnOJDlLh.dpuf
helpdesk-note.body-html:
1. Go to ciscovoicemail.msoe.edu
  2. Log in using your standard email credentials
  3. Click “Messaging Assistant”
  4. Mouse over the “Password” dropdown menu and choose change pin
  5. Using numbers ONLY type the password you want to use for your voice mail. It must be a minimum of 6 characters.
  6. Click save and your new voicemail password will be set instantly.
 
You can only change your password this way 1 time every 24 hours.
- See more at: http://www.msoe.edu/docs/DOC-1950#sthash.GnOJDlLh.dpuf

helpdesk-note.body:
Hi Mitch Colton, Issue: http://helpdesk.msoe.edu/helpdesk/tickets/2014
Dr. Colton indicated that voice messages left on his phone are not creating a VoiceMessage.wav file in his Outlook inbox.
Hello Sir,
It is possible that your Voicemail Mailbox is full. You could try going onto the online portal by Cisco to delete some of your old voicemails.
Go to ciscovoicemail.msoe.edu
Log in using your standard email credentials. (username, password) Click “Messaging Assistant”
You should be able to delete your old messages.
Let us know if this works for you.
Thanks Rishabh

helpdesk-note.body:
Hi Matt,
Under no circumstances can we extend your MSOE email access unless you are currently enrolled. What you can do is set up the alumni email and follow the steps to forward email sent to your msoe email to the alumni email. Even though you will not have access to your msoe email, people can still actively send to the address and, with that rule, any email you receive to it will be forwarded.
You will need to do this as soon as possible because you will lose access to the account six weeks after your graduation.

helpdesk-ticket.subject: Plotter Printing Information
helpdesk-ticket.description:
Paula called asking if the plotter is now usable since we moved. I told her yes and gave her the following information:
To print, the document must be either pdf or powerpoint.
The document must be sized to the desired poster size.
The plotter prints 36" wide and any length. A smaller width document will not be cut.
No solid/ink heavy backgrounds.
Printing will take roughly 15-20 minutes depending on poster size and content.

helpdesk-note.body:
Cameron,
This can probably go directly to Tier 2. You can either map the drive directly (you'll need a username and password with the access they want) or add it to the domain, so that it will map the O: drive by default to the access of the logged in user. We don't normally add outside computers to the domain, but if this is replacing a device, we probably had an exception for the original computer. Tier 2 will know how to perform either task.
Thanks

Howdy! I am in at WMSE right now and able to address the questions at hand.
I understand that new generic accounts will not be created. Will there be an issue with continuing to use an existing account? Currently, I am using the "A-Studio" account to log into the new computer. This has been an incredible obstacle for me over the past couple of weeks. - I seek to create a file share folder on this newest machine to replace all usage of the O: drive at WMSE. If this share can be created in a way to allow access via all WMSE folks, then this will be the base storage location for all air media shared amongst the various hosts. This is also critical because playback of this media is what allows us to fulfill our obligation to our underwriters and continue to procure the funding to stay on the air in the first place.
Please, any steps you can take to help me address computer access and common storage will be most welcome. Since I am only in Milwaukee one day a week, the sooner we can resolve these issues, the sooner I can assist the hosts at WMSE with their obligation to the station's underwriters as the current system is no longer tenable and relieve the station of any dependence on shared MSOE network storage.
Thanks a lot for your time and assistance.
Matt Rockwell 608-345-1972

helpdesk-note.body:
Hi Matt,
Correct we do not create generic account anymore. IT is also working toward getting rid of existing generic accounts. To resolve your two issues here are my suggestions.
We need to get you a domain account/MSOE email address and then add that account as an admin to the WMSE computers. In order to get you a domain account Tom will need to contact HR so they can input your information into the system. Once your information is entered an account will be created for you. Besides basic information HR will need your social security number and date of birth. I think Box.com would work best for a file share folder. You get unlimited space and it can be sync'd to peoples desktop using Box Sync. Everyone that would need access to it would need to create an account on Box.com using their MSOE email address. Then Tom would create a folder under his Box account and call it WMSE-Staff or whatever he wants and share it with everyone that needs access to it.
I am attaching couple Box.com documents for you to review. Let me know once HR has your information entered. I can make sure a domain account gets created for you. Are you in next Tuesday? I can stop by WMSE and help you get your domain account added as an admin and help you get Box.com setup on computers.
Mike Issue: http://helpdesk.msoe.edu/helpdesk/tickets/2046 Need map new audio computers drive to network on a new audio serving computer in our main studio. Need Access to the O drive.
Tom Crawford WMSE Krueger Hall x7247

helpdesk-note.body:
Mike, Thanks for writing. Tom C. is in the process of requesting an account for me.
Cloud shared storage space is unacceptable as a solution for us for a couple of reasons. Our access of these files is for audio playback over the air, thus the primary reason is latency. Also, in the event that a network connection is lost, our playback systems cannot be cut off from the playback media as dead air is the result of either of these situations. We will stand firm on our need for local shared storage for playback media.
Please keep in mind that we have obligations to fulfill not only to our listeners and underwriters, but also to the FCC to maintain our broadcast license.
Thanks again for your time and assistance. It's very much appreciated.
Matt Rockwell 608-345-1972

helpdesk-ticket.subject: Windows side-by-side configuration problem with laptop after installing Windows updates
helpdesk-ticket.description:
Hello Support, On Tuesday, October 13, 2015, Windows prompted me to install updates on my MSOE laptop. I installed the updates, but Windows informed me that the installation of a number of the updates failed. I did not have time to deal with the situation at that moment. At the end of the day, when I shut down my laptop, Windows began installing updates again. I stopped the process because I was leaving. That night, I searched the Microsoft site for a solution, and found a fix ("What to do when updates fail to install"). This seemed to repair the problem. Subsequently, when I booted up Windows, the OS indicated that it was configuring Windows, and then everything seemed to operate normally. On Thursday evening (October 15), when I logged into my laptop, Windows once again indicated that it was configuring, and then I successfully logged in. When I logged in and tried to access applications (Firefox, IE, Word), I received the following error message: 'The application has failed to start because its side-by-side configuration is incorrect. please see the application event log or use the command-line sxstrace.exe tool for more details." Using a personal laptop at home, I discovered some solutions to this problem. See https://support.microsoft.com/en-us/kb/2525435 http://www.chiefarchitect.com/support/article/KB-01046/message-the-application-has-failed-to-start-because-its-side-by-side-configuration-is-incorrect.html
http://answers.microsoft.com/en-us/windows/forum/windows_7-pictures/error-the-application-has-failed-to-start-because/df019c0d-746e-42d0-ad68-465e18e3f3ef?auth=1 The problem seems to be missing or conflicting C++ runtime components -- perhaps occurring the install of updates. Otherwise, I have not installed anything else that I am aware of.. i am out of the office today (October 16). In addition to running the library, I am teaching two online courses this quarter. I will work with a personal laptop today and this weekend to do my course materials on Blackboard. Is there anything you can suggest that I can do to repair the MSOE laptop over the weekend? I cannot access the Internet on the laptop, because the browsers do not function. Thanks, Gary Shimek Director of the Library / Assistant Professor x7181 shimek@msoe.edu
helpdesk-ticket.description-html:
Hello Support,

On Tuesday, October 13, 2015, Windows prompted me to install updates on my MSOE laptop.  I installed the updates, but Windows informed me that the installation of a number of the updates failed.  I did not have time to deal with the situation at that moment.  At the end of the day, when I shut down my laptop, Windows began installing updates again.  I stopped the process because I was leaving.  That night, I searched the Microsoft site for a solution, and found a fix ("What to do when updates fail to install").  This seemed to repair the problem.  Subsequently, when I booted up Windows, the OS indicated that it was configuring Windows, and then everything seemed to operate normally.  On Thursday evening (October 15), when I logged into my laptop, Windows once again indicated that it was configuring, and then I successfully logged in.  When I logged in and tried to access applications (Firefox, IE, Word), I received the following error message:

'The application has failed to start because its side-by-side configuration is incorrect. please see the application event log or use the command-line sxstrace.exe tool for more details."

Using a personal laptop at home, I discovered some solutions to this problem.  See https://support.microsoft.com/en-us/kb/2525435

http://www.chiefarchitect.com/support/article/KB-01046/message-the-application-has-failed-to-start-because-its-side-by-side-configuration-is-incorrect.html
http://answers.microsoft.com/en-us/windows/forum/windows_7-pictures/error-the-application-has-failed-to-start-because/df019c0d-746e-42d0-ad68-465e18e3f3ef?auth=1 

The problem seems to be missing or conflicting C++ runtime components -- perhaps occurring the install of updates.  Otherwise, I have not installed anything else that I am aware of..  

i am out of the office today (October 16).  In addition to running the library, I am teaching two online courses this quarter.  I will work with a personal laptop today and this weekend to do my course materials on Blackboard.  Is there anything you can suggest that I can do to repair the MSOE laptop over the weekend?  I cannot access the Internet on the laptop, because the browsers do not function.

Thanks,
Gary Shimek
Director of the Library / Assistant Professor
x7181
shimek@msoe.edu

helpdesk-note.body:
Hi Gary Shimek,
From what it seems, the reason for your error could be a multitude of things considering the updates could have reached out to pretty much anywhere.
I read further into the issue (thank you for the links, by the way) and I think I'd be able to give you more advice depending on which files are corrupted. From there we should be able to narrow down the issue and look further into solutions. http://answers.microsoft.com/en-us/windows/forum/windows_7-pictures/this-application-failed-to-start-because-side-by/7673bf12-87c2-48ca-b5ae-b8aa85e295dc Follow the instructions in the link provided above and if you could send me the results that would be great. In your situation, a reimage is a pretty common solution to such an issue. We would be glad to reimage it, but given that you do not want to reimage we can attempt a few other solutions first.
Thank you for your time and we hope to get to the bottom of this as soon as possible. If you find the instructions above to be difficult we would be glad to come by whenever you're back and do the troubleshooting ourselves. Issue: http://helpdesk.msoe.edu/helpdesk/tickets/2050 Hello Support,

'The application has failed to start because its side-by-side configuration is incorrect. please see the application event log or use the command-line sxstrace.exe tool for more details."

Using a personal laptop at home, I discovered some solutions to this problem.  See https://support.microsoft.com/en-us/kb/2525435

http://www.chiefarchitect.com/support/article/KB-01046/message-the-application-has-failed-to-start-because-its-side-by-side-configuration-is-incorrect.html
http://answers.microsoft.com/en-us/windows/forum/windows_7-pictures/error-the-application-has-failed-to-start-because/df019c0d-746e-42d0-ad68-465e18e3f3ef?auth=1 

The problem seems to be missing or conflicting C++ runtime components -- perhaps occurring the install of updates.  Otherwise, I have not installed anything else that I am aware of..  

i am out of the office today (October 16).  In addition to running the library, I am teaching two online courses this quarter.  I will work with a personal laptop today and this weekend to do my course materials on Blackboard.  Is there anything you can suggest that I can do to repair the MSOE laptop over the weekend?  I cannot access the Internet on the laptop, because the browsers do not function.

Thanks,
Gary Shimek
Director of the Library / Assistant Professor
x7181
shimek@msoe.edu

helpdesk-note.body:
Thanks for the reply, Help Desk -- I appreciate it. Thanks for the Microsoft information, too.
I ran the System File Checker tool. The results seem to indicate that there are two system files that Windows cannot repair. They appear to be d3d10warp.dll and DWrite.dll. Windows appears to have have detected one other corrupt file, but was able to repair it.
I have attached the sfcdetails.txt.
According to the instructions that you sent, the next step is to manually replace the files with known good files. Unfortunately, I don't have access to known good copies.
I will have to bring the laptop to the Help Desk on Monday morning. Would it be possible to manually replace the corrupt dll's with known good copies?
I'm not adverse to having the C:drive re-imaged -- it's just that it's difficult to be without the laptop for an extended period of time. I can see already that I'm going to have a problem posting the content that I needed to post on Blackboard this weekend. However, if re-imagining is the only option, then we'll have to do it. I was hoping we could simply replace the corrupt files. I do have all of my important data backed up. I will plan to bring the laptop to the Help Desk on Monday morning.
Thanks for all of your help.
Gary Shimek
Library

Hi Gary Shimek,

From what it seems, the reason for your error could be a multitude of things considering the updates could have reached out to pretty much anywhere.

I read further into the issue (thank you for the links, by the way) and I think I'd be able to give you more advice depending on which files are corrupted. From there we should be able to narrow down the issue and look further into solutions.

this application failed to start because side-by-side ...

Read more...



Follow the instructions in the link provided above and if you could send me the results that would be great. In your situation, a reimage is a pretty common solution to such an issue. We would be glad to reimage it, but given that you do not want to reimage we can attempt a few other solutions first.

Thank you for your time and we hope to get to the bottom of this as soon as possible. If you find the instructions above to be difficult we would be glad to come by whenever you're back and do the troubleshooting ourselves.

[#INC-2078]

helpdesk-note.body:
Hi Tyler Braun,
If you could stop by the Helpdesk, that would be great. You can also try clearing the credential manager. What happens when you click "Remember Me" in the Outlook sign in, is that Outlook stores those entered credentials in a program called "Credential Manager" changing or resetting your MSOE account password does not actually change the entries in this program. We can try clearing it manually, which should force Outlook to ask for your most recent credentials instead of using the outdated ones.
1. Open your start menu and type "Credential Manager" into the search bar. Click on it to open the program.
2. The Credential Manager window should appear. Near the bottom should be a section labeled "Generic Credentials" which should contain a saved credential labeled something along the lines of "MS.Outlook.youremailaddress". Click on that to expand it, and choose the option "Remove From Vault". When a warning message appears, click "Yes".
3. Close the Credential Manager. If Outlook is not already closed, close that as well. When you open Outlook again, it should prompt you for your new password and restore access.
Let me know if this doesn't work, and please stop by if you can so we can take a look at it.
